Here’s an updated version of the simple IRC client that supports the `/me` command to send an `ACTION` message instead of a `PRIVMSG`. The `/me` command is typically used in IRC to perform an action (like "doesnm waves") which would appear as "* doesnm waves" in chat.

Below is the complete code for the client:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Simple IRC Client with /me Command</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }
        #messages {
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            height: 300px;
            overflow-y: scroll;
            padding: 10px;
            background-color: white;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
        }
        #input {
            display: flex;
        }
        #message {
            flex: 1;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px;
            margin-left: 5px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>IRC Client with /me Command</h1>
    <div id="messages"></div>
    <div id="input">
        <input type="text" id="message" placeholder="Type a message or /me action..." />
        <button id="sendBtn">Send</button>
    </div>

    <script>
        const ws = new WebSocket('wss://irc.h4ks.com:8097');
        const messagesDiv = document.getElementById('messages');
        const input = document.getElementById('message');
        const sendBtn = document.getElementById('sendBtn');

        // Function to generate the username
        function generateUsername() {
            const randomNum = Math.floor(Math.random() * 10000).toString().padStart(4, '0');
            return `doesnm${randomNum}`;
        }

        const username = generateUsername();
        console.log(`Connecting as ${username}`);

        ws.onopen = () => {
            ws.send(`NICK ${username}`);
            ws.send(`USER ${username} 0 * :${username}`);
            ws.send('JOIN #lobby');
            ws.send(`PRIVMSG #lobby :hi ${username}, I am you`);
        };

        ws.onmessage = (event) => {
            const message = event.data;
            console.log(`Received: ${message}`);
            const messageElement = document.createElement('div');
            messageElement.textContent = message;
            messagesDiv.appendChild(messageElement);
            messagesDiv.scrollTop = messagesDiv.scrollHeight; // Auto scroll to bottom
        };

        sendBtn.onclick = () => {
            const messageText = input.value;
            if (messageText) {
                if (messageText.startsWith('/me ')) {
                    // Handle /me command
                    const actionText = messageText.substring(4); // Extract action text
                    ws.send(`PRIVMSG #lobby :\u0001ACTION ${actionText}\u0001`); // Send ACTION
                } else {
                    ws.send(`PRIVMSG #lobby :${messageText}`);
                }
                input.value = ''; // Clear input field
            }
        };

        // Optional: Send message with Enter key
        input.addEventListener('keypress', (event) => {
            if (event.key === 'Enter') {
                sendBtn.click();
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions:
1. Copy the complete code provided above into a text editor.
2. Save the file with an `.html` extension, such as `irc_client_with_me.html`.
3. Open the saved HTML file in a web browser to run the IRC client.

### How the `/me` Command Works:
- If you type a message starting with `/me ` (followed by an action), the input will be converted into an `ACTION` message and sent to the IRC channel.
- For example:
  - Typing `/me waves` will send `* doesnm waves` to the channel, where `doesnm` is your generated username.

### Notes:
- The `ACTION` command in IRC begins and ends with the escape character `\u0001`.
- This implementation retains simplicity and is suitable for basic usage; you can extend it with additional features as needed.
- Ensure that your browser permits secure WebSocket connections and that the IRC server is reachable on the specified port.

Creating an IRC client that visually resembles Telegram requires replicating its user interface closely. Below, I've crafted an HTML page that emulates Telegram's aesthetic, using similar styling for chat bubbles, message input, and an overall layout.

Please note that while the appearance can be styled to look like Telegram, the functionality will remain that of a simple IRC client, as previously discussed.

Here’s the complete code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>IRC Client Like Telegram</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #e6e6e6;
        }
        #chat-container {
            max-width: 600px;
            margin: auto;
            background-color: white;
            border-radius: 20px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
            overflow: hidden;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            height: 90vh;
        }
        #messages {
            flex: 1;
            overflow-y: auto;
            padding: 20px;
            border-bottom: 1px solid #f0f0f0;
        }
        .message {
            margin-bottom: 15px;
            max-width: 80%;
            border-radius: 20px;
            padding: 10px;
        }
        .message.received {
            background-color: #f1f0f0;
            align-self: flex-start;
            color: #333;
        }
        .message.sent {
            background-color: #0088cc;
            color: white;
            align-self: flex-end;
        }
        #input {
            display: flex;
            padding: 10px;
            border-top: 1px solid #f0f0f0;
            background-color: #fff;
        }
        #message {
            flex: 1;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 20px;
            margin-right: 10px;
            outline: none;
        }
        button {
            background-color: #0088cc;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 20px;
            padding: 10px 15px;
            cursor: pointer;
            transition: background-color 0.3s;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0077b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="chat-container">
        <div id="messages"></div>
        <div id="input">
            <input type="text" id="message" placeholder="Type a message or /me action..." />
            <button id="sendBtn">Send</button>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        const ws = new WebSocket('wss://irc.h4ks.com:8097');
        const messagesDiv = document.getElementById('messages');
        const input = document.getElementById('message');
        const sendBtn = document.getElementById('sendBtn');

        function generateUsername() {
            const randomNum = Math.floor(Math.random() * 10000).toString().padStart(4, '0');
            return `doesnm${randomNum}`;
        }

        const username = generateUsername();
        console.log(`Connecting as ${username}`);

        ws.onopen = () => {
            ws.send(`NICK ${username}`);
            ws.send(`USER ${username} 0 * :${username}`);
            ws.send('JOIN #lobby');
            ws.send(`PRIVMSG #lobby :hi ${username}, I am you`);
        };

        ws.onmessage = (event) => {
            const message = event.data;
            const messageElement = document.createElement('div');
            messageElement.classList.add('message', 'received');
            messageElement.textContent = message;
            messagesDiv.appendChild(messageElement);
            messagesDiv.scrollTop = messagesDiv.scrollHeight; // Auto scroll to bottom
        };

        sendBtn.onclick = () => {
            const messageText = input.value.trim();
            if (messageText) {
                let messageElement = document.createElement('div');
                if (messageText.startsWith('/me ')) {
                    const actionText = messageText.substring(4);
                    ws.send(`PRIVMSG #lobby :\u0001ACTION ${actionText}\u0001`);
                    messageElement.classList.add('message', 'sent');
                    messageElement.textContent = `* ${username} ${actionText}`;
                } else {
                    ws.send(`PRIVMSG #lobby :${messageText}`);
                    messageElement.classList.add('message', 'sent');
                    messageElement.textContent = messageText;
                }
                messagesDiv.appendChild(messageElement);
                messagesDiv.scrollTop = messagesDiv.scrollHeight; // Auto scroll to bottom
                input.value = ''; // Clear input field
            }
        };

        // Optional: Send message with Enter key
        input.addEventListener('keypress', (event) => {
            if (event.key === 'Enter') {
                sendBtn.click();
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions:
1. Copy the complete code above into a text editor.
2. Save the file with an `.html` extension, such as `irc_client_telegram_style.html`.
3. Open the saved HTML file in a web browser to view and use the IRC client.

### Key Features of the Design:
- **Layout**: The chat interface has a clean layout, with the input field at the bottom and messages above.
- **Message Bubbles**: Messages are styled to resemble Telegram chat bubbles, with sent messages appearing on the right and received messages on the left.
- **Colors and Fonts**: A color scheme similar to Telegram is used, with rounded edges for buttons and message bubbles.

### Notes:
- This implementation provides a visual mimicry of Telegram but retains its functionality as an IRC client.
- Make sure your browser allows secure WebSocket connections, and that the IRC server is reachable on the specified port.

